One of the freed Abuja-Kaduna train attack victims yesterday staged a lone protest in Kaduna. The female passenger, who refused to say her name, took to the streets to call for the release of the remaining 50 abducted passengers still in captivity. Among them, she said, is her husband. She told reporters at the Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ) secretariat in Kaduna that she had been unable to sleep well since her release.   Inmate graduates with 2nd Class Upper from Open University     Two shot dead, 16 abducted in Kaduna     After N2.5m fine, court threatens Evans with more penalties   She held a placard with the inscription: “I can’t sleep anymore when my loved ones are in the bush. Please Nigerians help towards their release.” She and 10 others were released after spending over 70 days in captivity. The woman said she keeps remembering that her husband and 49 other innocent persons are in the bush. She is calling on the government to do the needful and ensure that the remaining passengers are released without delay. She lamented that there are children and the aged amongst the captives in the forest exposed to rain, cold, harsh weather and wild animals, among others.